                <div class="tab-content">
                    <div class="tab-pane active" id="tab-script">
                        <div class="js-script-content-wrapper top-margin-script markdown-content">
                                                                                        <a href="https://github.com/knpuniversity/symfony/edit/master/knpu/extra-doctrine-collections/insert-many-to-many.md" target="_blank" class="btn btn-default btn-circle pull-right js-tooltip" title="Edit on GitHub"><span class="fa fa-pencil"></span></a>
                                                                    <p>The <em>big</em> question is: who is the best superhero of all time? Um, I mean, how
can we <em>insert</em> things into this join table? How can we join a <code>Genus</code> and a <code>User</code>
together?</p>
<p>Doctrine makes this <em>easy</em>... and yet... at the same time... kind of confusing!
First, you need to completely forget that a join table exists. Stop thinking about
the database! Stop it! Instead, your <em>only</em> job is to get a <code>Genus</code> object, put
one or more <code>User</code> objects onto its <code>genusScientists</code> property and then save. Doctrine
will handle the rest.</p>
<h2 id="setting-items-on-the-collection">Setting Items on the Collection <a class="headerlink" href="insert-many-to-many#setting-items-on-the-collection" title="Permalink to this headline"><i class="fa fa-link" aria-hidden="true"></i></a></h2>
<p>Let's see this in action! Open up <code>GenusController</code>. Remember <code>newAction()</code>? This isn't
a real page - it's just a route where <em>we</em> can play around and test out some code.
And hey, it <em>already</em> creates and saves a <code>Genus</code>. Cool! Let's associate a user
with it!</p>
<p>First, find a user with <code>$user = $em-&gt;getRepository('AppBundle:User')</code> then <code>findOneBy()</code>
with <code>email</code> set to <code>aquanaut1@example.org</code>:</p>
